  <div class="article-content">
    <section id="introduction" class="reveal">
  <p>You've worn the same daily disposable contact lenses for eight years. Same brand, same power, same base curve. Your eyes feel fine. You try to reorder and learn your prescription expired six weeks ago. Now you need a $200 appointment, a two-week wait, and a doctor to confirm what you already know: nothing has changed. In Sweden, you could walk to a vending machine. In Canada, you'd place the order and get on with your life. In the United States, you are purchasing a Class II medical device, and the government would like you to see a professional first. Every year. Whether you need to or not.</p>
</section>

<section id="the-safety-case-is-real-but-narrow" class="reveal">
  <h2>The safety case is real but narrow</h2>
  <p>Contact lenses sit on living tissue. An ill-fitting lens can starve the cornea of oxygen, scrape the epithelium, or incubate Pseudomonas aeruginosa into a vision-threatening infection. Microbial keratitis in daily-wear soft lenses runs between 1.9 and 4.1 cases per 10,000 wearers per year. Extended-wear lenses — the kind people sleep in — push that to 13 to 21 per 10,000. The CDC, which has faced criticism for underreporting in past eye health data due to reliance on voluntary reporting, estimates nearly one million U.S. healthcare visits annually for keratitis of all types, costing $175 million—figures that include non-contact-lens-related cases and may inflate the perceived risk for daily disposables. A 2015 CDC survey found 99% of contact lens wearers reported at least one risky hygiene behavior.</p>
  <p>These numbers justify a fitting exam. When someone first gets contact lenses, a professional should measure the cornea, assess tear quality, check for contraindications, and teach the wearer not to rinse lenses in tap water. For extended-wear lenses, ongoing monitoring is clinically defensible — the infection rate is five to ten times higher than daily wear, and complications tend to be more severe.</p>
  <p>But the U.S. system doesn't distinguish. It treats a first-time teenager trying monthlies and a 35-year-old reordering the same daily disposables she's worn since college as identical regulatory problems. They are not.</p>
</section>

<section id="daily-disposables-broke-the-argument" class="reveal">
  <h2>Daily disposables broke the argument</h2>
  <p>The single strongest justification for recurring professional oversight is hygiene compliance. Patients store lenses in contaminated cases. They top off old solution instead of replacing it. They overwear lenses designed for two weeks until the lenses are cloudy with protein deposits. The annual exam is supposed to catch the subclinical damage this behavior causes.</p>
  <p>Daily disposable lenses eliminate almost all of it. No case. No solution. No overnight storage. No protein buildup. No temptation to stretch a lens past its replacement date because you've already invested in cleaning it. You open a sterile blister pack in the morning, throw the lens away at night. The compliance problem that drives the majority of contact lens complications essentially vanishes.</p>
  <p>The data confirm this. A Scandinavian study found severe microbial keratitis requiring hospitalization occurred at a rate of 0.52 per 10,000 for daily disposable wearers — compared to 2.52 per 10,000 for extended-wear users. Nearly five times lower. A UCL and Moorfields Eye Hospital study published in <em>Ophthalmology</em>, funded by the UK's National Institute for Health Research and without disclosed industry ties, found reusable soft lens wearers had 3.8 times the odds of developing Acanthamoeba keratitis compared with daily disposable users, and estimated that 30–62% of AK cases in the UK could be prevented by switching from reusable to daily disposable lenses. Contact Lens Spectrum reported corneal infiltrative event rates of 0.2% per year for daily disposables versus 3.3% to 7.2% for reusable modalities.</p>
  <p>The CDC itself, in a 2016 MMWR analysis of a decade of FDA adverse event reports, noted that daily disposable wearers had lower infection risk and were infrequently listed in microbial keratitis reports. The agency that regulates contact lenses as medical devices is telling you the safest modality is daily disposables. The regulatory framework treats them exactly the same as the modality with five times the infection rate.</p>
</section>

<section id="twenty-five-countries-tried-it-differently" class="reveal">
  <h2>Twenty-five countries tried it differently</h2>
  <p>In 25 of 28 European Union countries, consumers can purchase contact lenses from stationary vending machines — no prescription verification at point of sale. Canada deregulated in 2010: you can order lenses online without submitting a prescription. The UK is more regulated — the Opticians Act 1989 requires a spectacle prescription within two years before fitting — but major online retailers like Lenstore state openly that they don't verify prescriptions at purchase.</p>
  <p>The AOA's response to international comparisons is to dismiss them, often citing unproven claims about U.S.-specific risks like higher obesity rates or diverse ethnic corneas potentially affecting lens fit; the FDA has called foreign safety data inapplicable to U.S. demographics without specifying which demographic difference would make a daily disposable lens more dangerous on an American cornea than a British one, though critics argue this is a stalling tactic lacking empirical support.</p>

  <div class="data-callout reveal"><p><strong>The missing study</strong></p><p>No published, peer-reviewed comparative study demonstrates higher rates of contact lens complications in countries with lax prescription enforcement versus the United States. The regulatory difference is decades old. If the American system were as essential as its proponents claim, someone should have been able to detect the bodies by now.</p></div>

  <p>The absence of that study is the most important fact in this debate. Not because absence of evidence is evidence of absence — but because the people with the strongest incentive to produce such evidence are the very professional associations defending the status quo. The AOA has filed 133 formal communications during a single FTC rule review. If the data existed, they would have found it.</p>
</section>

<section id="follow-the-exam-fee" class="reveal">
  <h2>Follow the exam fee</h2>
  <p>The contact lens exam is a pillar of optometric practice revenue. The Vision Council's Q3 2025 survey found that over 75% of contact lens users made a purchase within the past year, with exam activity remaining steady. The annual prescription requirement guarantees this cadence. An experienced daily disposable wearer who could safely reorder every three years represents lost revenue — not for one appointment, but compounded across 45 million wearers.</p>
  <p>A 2020 study in the Journal of Regulatory Economics found that the Fairness to Contact Lens Consumers Act — which merely required prescribers to release prescriptions so patients could shop elsewhere — led to a 13% reduction in optometrists' wages. The prescription requirement itself was untouched. The industry fought the FCLCA ferociously, then fought the FTC's implementation rules for two more decades. Every reform that loosens optometric control over the point of sale is treated as a patient safety crisis, regardless of evidence.</p>
  <p>The AOA filed more comments during the Eyeglass Rule review than 1-800 Contacts, the American Academy of Ophthalmology, and the National Association of Retail Optical Companies combined. It backed legislation to ban the automated verification robocalls that online retailers use to confirm prescriptions. It pushed for signed acknowledgment requirements that the FTC estimated would add $13 million in annual compliance costs. The consistent position: make purchasing harder, make exams more frequent, make every regulatory touchpoint stickier.</p>

  <aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"If the eye industry really believes these mandatory exams are so necessary, they should be required to give them for free."</p></aside>

  <p>That anonymous internet comment is not evidence. But it captures the structural problem with perfect economy: the people who profit financially from mandatory exams are the loudest voices insisting the exams are medically indispensable. In any other industry, we'd call that a conflict of interest. In optometry, we call it patient safety.</p>
</section>

<section id="online-retailers-arent-angels-either" class="reveal">
  <h2>Online retailers aren't angels either</h2>
  <p>The FTC found in 2018 that 1-800 Contacts — which controls over 50% of online lens sales — had orchestrated anticompetitive advertising agreements with 14 rival online retailers, suppressing price competition. Consumers paid higher prices because they couldn't see rival ads. The Second Circuit overturned the decision in 2021 on trademark grounds, but the underlying market dynamics were undisputed.</p>
  <p>The Coalition for Contact Lens Consumer Choice, which includes online retailers and big-box stores, lobbies for looser prescription rules. They have their own financial interests. The difference is that one side of this fight has the regulatory apparatus locked in its favor — and the complication data for daily disposable lenses does not support the lock.</p>
</section>

<section id="what-an-honest-system-would-do" class="reveal">
  <h2>What an honest system would do</h2>
  <p>Mandatory first fitting. No debate. A professional measures the cornea, assesses tear film, rules out contraindications, teaches insertion and hygiene.</p>
  <p>Annual exams for extended-wear and monthly reusable lenses. The complication rates justify it. Subclinical damage from hypoxia and deposit accumulation needs professional detection.</p>
  <p>Two- or three-year prescription renewals for daily disposable lenses in established wearers with stable prescriptions and no complicating conditions. This describes the plurality of American contact lens users. A brief symptom-screening questionnaire at reorder would flag the cases that need clinical follow-up without dragging the uncomplicated majority through a billable visit that exists to confirm what hasn't changed.</p>
  <p>This will not happen. The AOA will oppose it. State optometric boards will call it dangerous. The FDA will cite its classification framework. And 45 million Americans will keep scheduling appointments to be told what they already know, paying for the privilege of buying a product that half the developed world sells over the counter, because the people who write the rules are the same people who bill for the exams.</p>
  <p>The prescription requirement for daily disposable contact lenses, for experienced wearers with stable eyes, is not a medical necessity. It is a revenue model with a safety label.</p>
</section>

